tly to address some of these twenty-first-century challenges. The book examines the possible implications of such a re-reading of Kant for democracy, the human-animal relation, criminal law and punishment, as well as for a global constitutional order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitution (Philosophy). 0aConstitutional lawxPhilosophy. 0aDeconstruction. 4aPolitics and Law : Constitutional Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Law. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849173840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438491738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438491738/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles